<paragraph id="8B9E0A5D6717E060B3CDF83FFBA10EFA" blockId="20.[151,1436,1766,2016]" lastBlockId="21.[151,1437,151,465]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="82" pageId="20" pageNumber="81">
The most prominent and unique trait of the medium to large-sized 
<taxonomicName id="4C2171DE6717E061B097F83CFBF30888" baseAuthorityName="Curtis" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[925,1052,1989,2016]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysopidae" genus="Apertochrysa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ventralis">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6717E061B097F83CFBF30888" box="[925,1052,1989,2016]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="81">A. ventralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the presence of black abdominal sternites (
<figureCitation id="131A16D86716E060B20FFF6DFEB80FE5" box="[261,343,151,178]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1341,1365]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,489,1318]" captionTargetId="figure-163@21.[151,1436,489,1318]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 16. Apertochrysa ventralis with black ventral side of the abdomen, entirely black ccv, and large black spots on the prothorax (female from Claro, Ticino, Switzerland)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6531332" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6531332/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="82">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) and the black spot ventrally and on the prothorax. Body coloration grass-green or bluish-green. Tips of the palps dark. Face all green. Vertex green or yellowish-green, sometimes with two brown spots. Scape rarely (5%) with black caudal dots. Interantennal spot usually a very characteristic inverted clove shape (
<figureCitation id="131A16D86716E060B64CFF25FA780FAE" box="[1350,1431,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1150,1174]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,194,1109]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[151,1436,181,1127]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Shapes of interantennal spot in the European species of the prasina group." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6531308" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6531308/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="82">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="131A16D86716E060B39DFEF9FF5A0E4A" box="[151,181,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[401,1187,669,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-266@22.[401,1187,669,1885]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 17. Apertochrysa ventralis with black dots on vertex and an elongated clove-shaped interantennal spot (female from Agarone, Ticino, Switzerland)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6531334" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6531334/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="82">17</figureCitation>
), but more rarely pear- or Y-shaped. Subantennal sutures usually pale, but 13% had red or brown sutures. Female forewings 13.0–16.0 mm, male forewings 11.0–15.0 mm. Costal crossveins completely dark, males with furwings. Dark portion of im cell 12–30%, usually in one piece. Prothorax with one or two pairs of large brown or black spots. Three lateral prothoracic spots large, often one black, two brown. Dorsal abdomen usually without spots, 20% had single pairs of spots on some or most of the segments. The eggs are deposited singly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33B59D66716E060B3CDFE4CFD0F0E86" box="[199,736,438,465]" pageId="21" pageNumber="82" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9E0A5D6716E060B3CDFE4CFD0F0E86" blockId="21.[151,1437,151,465]" box="[199,736,438,465]" pageId="21" pageNumber="82">
<emphasis id="B955D64F6716E060B3CDFE4CFE8C0E87" bold="true" box="[199,355,438,464]" pageId="21" pageNumber="82">Distribution:</emphasis>
Europe, mainly the northern half.
</paragraph>
